title_narrative: Providing Logistical Support and Facilitation Services for Cross Border Humanitarian Relief Operations of Humanitarian Actors Operating from Turkey to Syria
description_narrative:
Ever since the beginning of the conflict in Syria, the Turkish Red Crescent has been actively involved in the delivery of vital humanitarian relief supplies to those affected. As a part of these services, the ‘Syria Crisis Humanitarian Relief Operations’ of the TRC has been launched on April 29, 2011. In addition, the TRC has been providing facilitation services for the Cross-Border delivery of humanitarian relief supplies since 2012. The TRC’s facilitation services for partner humanitarian organizations include but are not limited to assisting humanitarian organizations in the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria, enabling import and export with waivers, fast tracking at the border crossings, enabling the use of additional humanitarian aid border crossings, coordination of cross-border shipments to avoid prolonged waiting times at the border crossings as well as to maintain a comprehensive record for the humanitarian relief supplies that have been delivered. In addition, the TRC maintains close dialogue with both humanitarian relief partners as well as Turkish authorities in order to ensure that rules and regulations regarding customs formalities, cross-border delivery of humanitarian relief supplies as well as VAT exemption applications of NGO’s are undertaken in accordance with required steps. 
Since 2012, an average of 500 humanitarian relief trucks per month have been facilitated to beneficiaries in need in Syria as a part of the Cross-Border facilitation services. In the year 2019, a total of 3,999 trucks of humanitarian relief materials have been delivered Cross-Border through TRC assistance. In 2020, as of end of January, 668 number of trucks have been facilitated through TRC. In emergency cases, TRC has the capacity to facilitate more than 1.500 humanitarian relief trucks per month. Since the beginning of TRC’s facilitation activities in 2012, a total of 48,565 trucks of humanitarian relief supplies have been facilitated. 
TRC’s border relief services are important for the Cross-Border response of the humanitarian community because of its capacity to undertake these services through humanitarian border crossing points. In the event of any closures of commercial border crossing points from Turkey into Syria, the TRC is thus able to ensure that the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria continues through humanitarian channels. The sectoral breakdown of the humanitarian relief items facilitated by the TRC are food items % 38, NFI 35 %, Health 16 %, WASH 4 %, Shelter 4%. 
As a part of its humanitarian relief operations, the TRC coordinates its activities for the Cross-Border response from its ‘Syria Humanitarian Relief Operations Coordination Center’ located in Gaziantep. In addition, the TRC has cross-border facilitation activities in Gaziantep, Kilis, Hatay, Şanlıurfa and Mardin in order to facilitate the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies through 14 Border Relief Points. The Syria Humanitarian Relief Operations of the TRC utilizes 96 staff members.  
This project is vital in ensuring that the total amount of humanitarian assistance facilitated to date by the TRC, which has reached in excess of 1.06 Billion USD, continues to increase. Thus humanitarian organizations will be encouraged to use humanitarian channels when delivering assistance to beneficiaries in Syria. These services enable the keeping of a comprehensive record by the TRC in regards to the type and amount of humanitarian relief supplies delivered. These records are kept under a strictly confidential status by the TRC thus ensuring the privacy of the relevant humanitarian organization. Data regarding the total amount of humanitarian relief supplies delivered are used as a guide to fill existing gaps in the delivery of the humanitarian relief supplies.
reporting_org_narrative: United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs
other_identifier_owner_org_narrative: United Nations OCHA Financial Tracking Service (UN OCHA FTS)

title_narrative: Facilitation of Cross Border Operations and Logistics Support for the Humanitarian Actors Operating from Turkey to Syria
description_narrative:
The Turkish Red Crescent has been actively in the field ever since the beginning of the conflict in Syria. TRC actively implied in the delivery of crucial humanitarian relief supplies to those affected. As a result of humanitarian aid, the ‘Syria Crisis Humanitarian Relief Operations’ of the TRC has been launched in April 2011. Since 2012 the TRC has been providing facilitation services for the Cross-Border delivery of humanitarian relief supplies. Facilitation services that TRC providing for partner humanitarian organizations include but are not limited to enabling import and export with waivers, enabling the use of additional humanitarian aid border crossings, assisting humanitarian organizations in the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria, fast-tracking at the border crossings, coordination of cross-border shipments to avoid prolonged waiting times at the border crossings as well as to maintain a comprehensive record for the humanitarian relief supplies that have been delivered. 

Moreover, the TRC maintains a close dialogue with both humanitarian relief partners as well as Turkish authorities in order to ensure that rules and regulations regarding customs formalities, cross-border delivery of humanitarian relief supplies as well as VAT exemption applications of NGOs are undertaken in accordance with required steps. 

TRC’s border relief services are important for the Cross-Border response of the humanitarian community because of its capacity to undertake these services through humanitarian border crossing points. In the event of any closures of commercial border crossing points from Turkey into Syria, the TRC is thus able to ensure that the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria continues through humanitarian channels. 

From 2012 up until the present day, the sectoral breakdown of the humanitarian relief supplies delivered to beneficiaries is as follows 38 % food items, 36 % NFI, 16 % Health, 4 % WASH and 4 % Shelter. In this way, humanitarian organizations will be encouraged to use humanitarian channels when delivering assistance to beneficiaries in Syria. title_narrative: Logistical Support for Cross Border Operations for Humanitarian Actors Operating from Turkey into Syria
description_narrative: The “Syria Crisis Humanitarian Relief Operation” has been launched by the Turkish Red Crescent (TRC) on April 29, 2011 in response to the escalating conflict in the Syrian Arab Republic. The TRC has been providing facilitation since 2012 for the logistics of the cross border operations of all humanitarian actors responding to Syria. Due to the escalating humanitarian crisis across the border, the TRC has consistently increased the scope of its activities. Support for these activities was provided by the Turkey Humanitarian Fund (THF) under the framework of the ‘Logistical Support for Cross Border Operations for Humanitarian Actors Operating from Turkey into Syria’ project. Facilitation services of the TRC encompasses assisting humanitarian organizations in the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria, enabling import and export with waivers, initiating facilitation services in coordination with the applications of the NGO’s for exemption from Value Added Tax (VAT) for the delivery of humanitarian supplies, fast tracking at the border crossings, enabling the use of additional humanitarian aid border crossings, coordination of cross-border shipments to avoid congestion and maintaining a record for the humanitarian relief supplies delivered. Since its inception, 43.496 trucks of humanitarian relief supplies have been delivered across the border through the TRC (40 % Food Items, 36 % NFI, 15 % Health Supplies, 4 % WASH, 4 % Shelter and Education support). As a result, an average of 500 trucks a month of humanitarian relief supplies have reached the beneficiaries. Through the coordination center of the TRC, there are 108 staff employed who work to ensure the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies. The TRC operates out of Gaziantep, Kilis, Hatay, Şanlıurfa and Mardin in order to facilitate the delivery of humanitarian aid supplies through 14 Border Relief Points. The total amount of border relief assistance facilitated by the TRC has reached an amount in excess of 955 Million USD. The continuation of these activities of the TRC requires a substantial investment in terms of the human resources allocated as well as the logistical infrastructure in place. This project ensures that the operational capacity of the TRC in regards to the Humanitarian Relief Operations for the Syria Crisis is strengthened to support the activities of cross border humanitarian partners which are humanitarian organizations whom seek the facilitation services of the TRC. As a result of this project, and taking into account the analysis carried out during the previous phase of this project to strengthen the current operational modalities (annexes), the humanitarian organizations will be encouraged to use humanitarian channels when delivering relief assistance to the beneficiaries in Syria. This will ensure that the relief supplies reach their destination efficiently (avoiding prolonged waiting times often encountered at commercial channels) and to maintain a record of humanitarian relief supplies delivered. A record of the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies is crucial in determining the gaps in the relief efforts as well as avoiding duplication of services delivered to a war-torn country where demand always exceeds supply. The records are kept confidential, used for assisting needs analysis purposes. The TRC is able to access the areas in need due to its transparent, neutral stance with no affiliation with any political or military factions within Syria. The TRC gives its partners support for abiding by the regulations in place in regards to the cross-border delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria.
reporting_org_narrative: United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs

title_narrative: Logistical Support for Cross Border Operations for Humanitarian Actors Operating from Turkey into Syria in the Scope of the Emergency Response for North West Syria
description_narrative:
The Turkish Red Crescent (TRC) has been implementing the ‘Syria Humanitarian Relief Operation’ since April 29, 2011 in order to respond to the humanitarian needs arising from the conflict ongoing in the Syrian Arab Republic. An integral part of these activities include providing logistics support for the cross border operations of all humanitarian actors responding to the Syrian conflict. These support activities include but are not limited to assisting in the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies into Syria by humanitarian organizations responding to the crisis, enabling import and export activities with waivers, continuing dialogue activities with Turkish authorities to enable Value Added Tax (VAT) exemption for the delivery of humanitarian supplies through humanitarian corridors, coordination of cross-border shipments to avoid congestion and ensuring that all records of the type and amount of humanitarian relief materials delivered across the border through humanitarian channels are maintained on a real time basis. 
Since April 2019, there has been an increase in aerial bombardment as well as shelling by regime forces in Southern Idlib, Northern Hama and Western Aleppo. This has resulted in more than 450,000 IDP’s fleeing towards the Northern parts of Idlib according to the Camp Coordination and Camp Management (CCCM) Cluster reports. The TRC camps in the Dana / Idlib region have experienced the effects of this IDP flow into especially the Dana sub-district. The already stretched resources of all IDP camps within Northern Idlib have had to respond to the needs of these additional arrivals. The majority of these newly arrived IDP’s are women and children, thus constituting the most vulnerable segments. 
Therefore, the continuation of the Humanitarian Relief Operations has become vital for the wellbeing of those affected in the Idlib region. As it stands, the total number of border relief assistance facilitated by the TRC has reached 1.014 Billion USD since 2012, which marks the beginning of the facilitation of the Cross-Border delivery of humanitarian relief supplies by the TRC. (Cover Page Comment 4 Response) Yearly breakdown 2012 / $25.904.596,89 - 2013 / $183.399.291,55 - 2014 / $207.325.974,35 - 2015 / $155.567.248,16 - 2016 / $205.574.885,94 - 2017 / $116.961.110,32 - 2018 / $79.915.282,99 - 2019 / $45.170.775,76. 2.402 Donors since August 2012 – (166 International NGO – 365 Domestic NGO) have been using these services (TRC Border Crossing Facilitation services are only available for humanitarian activities. 
In terms of the humanitarian assistance provided to those in need in Idlib, there are 8 Border Relief Points utilized by the TRC in both Hatay and Kilis. Three of these are in Kilis while five are in Hatay. It is essential to ensure that the alternative border crossings in Kilis are kept active in case the security situation on the ground prevents access through Hatay. When taking into account the entire logistical support activities by the TRC, a total of 46,534 trucks of humanitarian relief supplies have been facilitated across the border into Syria. Of these we see that 38 % are Food Items, 35 % are NFI, 16 % are Health, 4 % in WASH as well as 4 % in Shelter. 
The records maintained by the TRC in terms of the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies across the border are kept confidential however, vital statistics which assist in needs and gap analyses are regularly shared with the authorities responsible for the coordination of humanitarian relief activities such as UN OCHA. The TRC access across the border relief points as well as its neutral and transparent stance in regards to any political or military factions in Syria ensures humanitarian materials are able to reach areas in Syria where the beneficiaries are in the most need. A monthly activity report with infographics will be shared with UNOCHA and the Logistics Cluster to ensure overview of operations are coordinated with each organization.
reporting_org_narrative: United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs

The records maintained by the TRC in terms of the delivery of humanitarian relief supplies across the border are kept confidential however, vital statistics which assist in needs and gap analyses are regularly shared with the authorities responsible for the coordination of humanitarian relief activities such as UN OCHA. The TRC access across the border relief points as well as its neutral and transparent stance in regards to any political or military factions in Syria ensures humanitarian materials are able to reach areas in Syria where the beneficiaries are in the most need. A monthly activity report with infographics will be shared with UNOCHA and the Logistics Cluster to ensure overview of operations are coordinated with each organization.

location_description_narrative: U.S. assistance to Afghanistan is designed to cement and build upon the gains of more than a dozen years of democratic governance and ensure the country remains a key ally to the United States and the region in the fight against international terrorism. This request takes into account the fragile progress made by the new Afghan administration in its first year. Facing security and economic challenges exacerbated by international military and development drawdowns and working through the difficult politics of a unity government, the government managed its way through the 2014 fiscal crisis inherited from the previous administration and avoided a fiscal crisis in 2015, selected a majority of cabinet members, re-established its relationship with the IMF, and took action to reduce corruption and waste in government procurements. In September 2015, the government and its international partners agreed upon a new accountability framework focused on the key challenges of corruption, economic growth, fiscal sustainability, and human rights. The government also established a New Development Partnership (NDP) with the United States that incentivizes ambitious development reform targets over the coming four years. Moving forward, Afghanistan will have to fight an emboldened Taliban insurgency, prevent the expansion of the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant's emerging presence, and revive a stagnant economy. President Obama recognized the importance of our partnership with Afghanistan in October 2015 when he announced that U.S. troops would remain in Afghanistan in greater numbers than originally planned through 2016 and into 2017 in order to better train and assist Afghan security forces in their fight against the insurgency. The United States' continued strategic partnership takes on increased importance as they enable sustainable development, help improve security, and calm the nerves of Afghanistan's neighbors who fear the U.S. government would withdraw its robust support for Afghanistan and the broader region. U.S. civilian assistance is focused on building sustainable and accountable Afghan institutions that provide citizens with security and the essential health, education and public services they need to invest in the future of their country. The FY 2017 Request prioritizes the preservation of past achievements, seeks to stimulate private sector led economic growth, and supports the Afghan government's progress in strengthening its capacity and stewardship. Significant resources will continue to support Afghan women and girls as they boldly advocate for their rightful role in all aspects of Afghan society. U.S. assistance will also focus on easing the transition from humanitarian assistance to development programming.The FY 2017 request of $1.3 billion will facilitate the continuation of nationwide development programs and conditional incentive programs like the NDP that are necessary to bring Afghanistan closer to long-term self-reliance. Programs will continue to work to facilitate economic growth, support improvements in the justice sector, and sustain gains in health, education, and women's rights. U.S. programs in Afghanistan will continue to promote transparency and accountability and fight corruption. This request is consistent with U.S. commitments made at the Tokyo and London Conferences to sustain support to Afghanistan through 2017 at or near levels of the last decade.

title_narrative: Vanuatu: Cyclone Pam - Humanitarian Assistance
description_narrative:
Tropical Cyclone Pam struck Vanuatu on 13-14 March 2015 resulting in 11 deaths, affecting the livelihoods of around 195,000 people (over half the population) and causing severe damage to infrastructure. DFAT led the Australian Government response, providing a total of around AUD 50 million. This included over AUD 10 million in humanitarian relief, which is managed through this investment.

Humanitarian relief funding was allocated through the following partners for implementation from March to December 2015: Humanitarian Partnership Agreement (Oxfam, World Vision, Care and Save the Children); Australian Red Cross; UNICEF; Australian Medical Assistance Team; Urban Search and Rescue teams; HK Logistics; and the DFAT Crisis Response Team.

title_narrative: Sudan - Emergency Assistance Program to Flood Victims
description_narrative: This operation is a US$ 500,000 emergency assistance program to support Victims of Floods in Kassala City. The program is part of a larger operation in which a number of bilateral donors and other multilateral organizations are participating. This larger operation is being coordinated by the Kassala Emergency Forum of the Republic of Sudan. The proposed humanitarian relief assistance entails the provision of kits to prevent cholera and water-borne disease, drugs and supplies, spraying equipment and chemicals for environmental sanitation. It complements the assistance provided by other donors in different areas of need.

La présente opération est un programme d'assistance d'urgence de 500 000 USD destiné à venir en aide aux victimes des inondations dans la ville de Kassala. Le programme fait partie d’une opération plus vaste à laquelle participent un certain nombre de donateurs bilatéraux et d’autres organisations multilatérales. Cette opération plus vaste est coordonnée par le Forum d’urgence de Kassala, en République du Soudan. L’aide humanitaire proposée comporte la fourniture de kits de prévention du choléra et des maladies d'origine hydrique, de médicaments et de fournitures, d'équipement de pulvérisation et de produits chimiques pour l'assainissement de l'environnement. Elle compléte l'assistance fournie par d'autres donateurs dans différents domaines de besoins.

The main goal of the proposed humanitarian relief assistance is to mitigate health-related effects of the floods in the Kassala city. The specific objective is to control the outbreaks of malaria, cholera and other communicable diseases among the flood victims.  The incidence and prevalence of these diseases have significantly increased in flood-affected areas where about 35.000 people have been displaced and housed in temporary accommodation.

L'aide humanitaire proposée vise principalement à atténuer les conséquences des inondations sur la santé de la ville de Kassala. L’objectif spécifique est de contrôler les épidémies de paludisme, de choléra et d’autres maladies transmissibles parmi les victimes des inondations. L'incidence et la prévalence de ces maladies ont considérablement augmenté dans les zones touchées par les inondations, où environ 35 000 personnes ont été déplacées et hébergées dans des logements temporaires.
The beneficiaries are the Sudanese government and the people of Kassala city.
Les bénéficiaires sont le gouvernement soudanais et les populations de la ville de Kassala.

title_narrative: Zambia - Emergency Humanitarian Food Assistance to Flood Victims
description_narrative: This Bank emergency humanitarian relief assistance is to complement the Government’s efforts to alleviate the suffering of the flood affected population in the 19 districts of Zambia. The grant funds will be used to purchase food and inputs for off-season winter cultivation, as well as associated costs of transportation and distribution of food rations to the beneficiaries, administrative charges and audit. Therefore, it is proposed that the total contribution of US$500,000 would be used for buying approximately 1,292 tons of maize at US$374,680, 50 tons of early maturing seed maize at US$80,000 and 0.496 tons of assorted vegetable seeds at US$20,000. A balance of US$25,320 would be used for transportation and logistics.

La présente opération d’aide humanitaire d’urgence vient compléter les efforts du Gouvernement visant à atténuer les souffrances de la population touchée par les inondations dans les 19 districts de la Zambie. Les fonds de la subvention serviront à acheter de la nourriture et des intrants pour la culture hivernale hors saison, ainsi que des coûts associés au transport et à la distribution de rations alimentaires aux bénéficiaires, aux frais administratifs et à l'audit. Il est ainsi proposé que la contribution totale de 500 000 USD serve à acheter environ 1 292 tonnes de maïs à 374 680 USD, 50 tonnes de maïs à germes précoces à 80 000 USD et 0,496 tonne de semences de légumes assorties à 20 000 USD. Un solde de 25 320 dollars des États-Unis serait utilisé pour le transport et la logistique.

L’aide humanitaire d’urgence proposée par la Banque a pour objectif d’aider et de compléter les efforts du Gouvernement visant à atténuer les souffrances des populations touchées par les inondations, principalement dans les provinces du Nord-Ouest, de l’Ouest, de l’Est, du Centre et du Nord.

The objective of the proposed Bank’s emergency humanitarian relief assistance is to assist and supplement the Government’s efforts to alleviate the suffering of the flood affected populations mainly in North-western, Western, Eastern, Central and Northern Provinces.
The project will target vulnerable households who do not have access to food as a result of the floods, with the primary objective of saving lives, and preserving livelihoods.

Le présent projet ciblera les ménages vulnérables qui n'ont pas accès à la nourriture à la suite des inondations, avec pour objectif principal de sauver des vies et de préserver les moyens de subsistance.

title_narrative: Zimbabwe - Humanitarian Emergency Assistance to The 2005 Drought Victims
description_narrative: The proposed Bank emergency humanitarian relief assistance projet aims to the alleviation of the suffering of the drought-affected victims in Zimbabwe. It is a Relief food assistance which will be channelled through targeted food distribution to households with insufficient crop production (as a result of insufficient rainfall), as well as those with no livestock or other sources of income (remittances, wage labour, etc) to purchase food and other basic needs; and widows, orphans, female- and elderly-headed households without visible means of survival. This assistance will be specifically targeted to provinces and districts most affected by poor rainfall. The total grant amount will be limited to the approved country ceiling of US$500,000 (five hundred thousand).

Le projet d'aide humanitaire d'urgence proposé par la Banque vise à atténuer les souffrances des victimes de la sécheresse au Zimbabwe. Il s’agit d’une aide alimentaire de secours qui sera acheminée par le biais d’une distribution ciblée de vivres aux ménages dont la production agricole est insuffisante (insuffisance de pluie), ainsi qu’à ceux qui n’ont pas d’élevage ni d’autres sources de revenus (envois de fonds, travail salarié, etc.) pour acheter de la nourriture et autres besoins de base; et les veuves, les orphelins, les ménages dirigés par des femmes et des personnes âgées sans moyens de survie visibles. Cette aide ciblera plus particulièrement les provinces et les districts les plus touchés par les faibles précipitations. Le montant total de la subvention est limité au plafond approuvé de 500 000 USD (cinq cent mille) par pays.
The objective of the proposed Bank emergency humanitarian relief assistance is to contribute to the alleviation of the suffering of the drought-affected victims in Zimbabwe.
L’aide humanitaire d’urgence proposée par la Banque a pour objectif de contribuer à atténuer les souffrances des victimes de la sécheresse au Zimbabwe.

This project targets vulnerable individuals and households with the primary objective of saving lives and preserving livelihoods, and will be distributed through programming categories such as Food Security, Health and Nutrition, HIV/AIDS, and Education.

Ce projet cible les individus et les ménages vulnérables ayant pour objectif principal de sauver des vies et de préserver les moyens de subsistance, et sera réparti par le biais de catégories de programmes telles que Sécurité alimentaire, Santé et nutrition, VIH / sida et Éducation.

title_narrative: Emergency Food Assistance to Populations Affected By Drought
description_narrative: The present intervention is relative to the Emergency Food Assistance to Populations Affected By Drought. It's designed because the Mozambique was affected by natural disasters in both 2007 and 2008. While still recovering from the devastating floods of 2007, Mozambique once again experienced major flooding in four central provinces along the Zambezi River basin in early 2008. The 2008 floods are the consequence of high levels of rainfall in Mozambique during late December 2007 and January 2008, compounded by persistent heavy rains in neighboring countries (Zambia, Zimbabwe and Malawi). The African Development Bank’s emergency humanitarian relief assistance is to assist and supplement the Government’s efforts to alleviate the suffering of the flood and drought affected populations mainly in Zambezia, Tete, Maputo and Inhambane. The relief food assistance targets vulnerable households who do not have access to food as a result of the floods and drought, with the primary objective of saving lives, and preserving livelihoods.

La présente intervention porte sur l'aide alimentaire d'urgence aux populations touchées par la sécheresse. Il a été conçu car le Mozambique a été touché par des catastrophes naturelles en 2007 et 2008. Tout en se remettant des inondations dévastatrices de 2007, le Mozambique a de nouveau connu d'importantes inondations dans quatre provinces centrales du bassin du Zambèze au début de 2008. Les inondations de 2008 sont la conséquence de fortes précipitations à la fin décembre 2007 et en janvier 2008 au Mozambique, aggravées par les fortes pluies persistantes dans les pays voisins (Zambie, Zimbabwe et Malawi). L’aide humanitaire d’urgence fournie par la Banque Africaine de Développement doit aider et compléter les efforts déployés par le Gouvernement pour atténuer les souffrances des populations touchées par les inondations et la sécheresse, principalement à Zambezia, Tete, Maputo et Inhambane. Elle vise les ménages vulnérables qui n'ont pas accès à la nourriture à la suite des inondations et de la sécheresse, l'objectif premier étant de sauver des vies et de préserver leurs moyens de subsistance.

The objective of the proposed Bank emergency humanitarian relief assistance is to contribute to the Government of Mozambique and WFP's efforts in providing food assistance to reduce the food insecurity situation of the vulnerable population affected by drought and recent cyclone.

L'objectif de l'aide humanitaire d'urgence proposée par la Banque est de contribuer aux efforts déployés par le Gouvernement du Mozambique et le PAM pour fournir une aide alimentaire visant à réduire la situation d'insécurité alimentaire des populations vulnérables touchées par la sécheresse et le récent cyclone.
The operation targets vulnerable households who do not have access to food as a result of the floods and drought, with the primary objective of saving lives, and preserving livelihoods.

L'opération cible les ménages vulnérables qui n'ont pas accès à la nourriture à la suite des inondations et de la sécheresse, l'objectif premier étant de sauver des vies et de préserver les moyens de subsistance.
